    h2 Remote Deployment of Microsoft Teams
    p
      | Going almost unnoticed, Microsoft has released MSI installers for Microsoft Teams. This enables organizations to leverage System Center Configuration Manager, Group Policy, or any 3rd party distribution mechanisms for broad deployments of Microsoft Teams. Admins can download the installation bits in the following locations:
    ul
      li
        a(href='http://aka.ms/teams32bitmsi') Microsoft Teams 32-bit MSI installer
      li
        a(href='http://aka.ms/teams64bitmsi') Microsoft Teams 64-bit MSI installer
    p
      | Target machines will require Windows 7, .NET 4.5, and 3 GB of disk space for the installation. For more information on the deployment view Microsoft&rsquo;s 
      a(href='https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/MicrosoftTeams/msi-deployment') documentation
      | .
  section
    h2 Microsoft Teams &ndash; All Company team
    p
      | The following section is designed to assist you with creating an All Company team in Microsoft Teams. The team can then be used to communicate and collaborate with your entire organization. Unfortunately, the max number of members in a team is 2,500. If your organization is larger than 2,500 users, you cannot use a single team to communicate. Due to the one-to-many communication method of Microsoft Teams, I personally wouldn&rsquo;t recommend having a team larger than 1,000 members. Communication of over 1,000 employees is best implemented using SharePoint and/or Yammer.
    p Microsoft has documented a similar command shell:
    ul
      li
        a(href='https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/MicrosoftTeams/scripts/powershell-script-sample-create-company-wide-team')
          | https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/MicrosoftTeams/scripts/powershell-script-sample-create-company-wide-team
      li
        a(href='https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/MicrosoftTeams/company-wide-team-creation-powershell')
          | https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/MicrosoftTeams/company-wide-team-creation-powershell
    p
      | To run the following commands, you must be able to connect to Azure AD &amp; Microsoft Teams using PowerShell. Connecting to Office 365 PowerShell with a user that has MFA enabled is more difficult. If you haven&rsquo;t connected to Office 365 PowerShell before and have MFA enabled, it&rsquo;s recommended to temporarily disable MFA or create a Global Admin without MFA for one-time use.
    pre.code
      p # Beginning of Script
      br
      p param(
      p   [Parameter(Mandatory=$true, HelpMessage=&quot;Name of team for the All Company Team (Recommended: Company&quot;)]
      p   [System.String]$TeamName,
      br
      p   [Parameter(Mandatory=$true, HelpMessage=&quot;Username of a global admin account&quot;)]
      p   [System.String]$GlobalAdminUsername,
      br
      p   [Parameter(Mandatory=$true, HelpMessage=&quot;Password of the global admin account&quot;)]
      p   [System.String]$GlobalAdminPassword
      p )
      br
      p $encryptedPassword = ConvertTo-SecureString -AsPlainText -Force -String $GlobalAdminPassword
      br
      p Write-Host &quot;Install NuGet (Used to install Microsoft Teams module)&quot; -ForegroundColor Cyan
      p Install-PackageProvider -Name NuGet -MinimumVersion 2.8.5.201 -Force
      br
      p Write-Host &quot;Install Azure AD PowerShell&quot; -ForegroundColor Cyan
      p Install-Module AzureAD -Force
      br
      p Write-Host &quot;Install Microsoft Teams PowerShell&quot; -ForegroundColor Cyan
      p Install-Module MicrosoftTeams -Force
      br
      p Write-Host &quot;Connect to Azure AD&quot; -ForegroundColor Cyan
      p $cred = New-Object -typename System.Management.Automation.PSCredential -argumentlist $GlobalAdminUsername, $encryptedPassword
      br
      p Connect-AzureAD -Credential $cred
      p Write-Host &quot;Connect to Microsoft Teams&quot; -ForegroundColor Cyan
      p $cred = New-Object -typename System.Management.Automation.PSCredential -argumentlist $GlobalAdminUsername, $encryptedPassword
      br
      p Connect-MicrosoftTeams -Credential $cred
      br
      p Write-Host &quot;Get all Microsoft Office 365 Users&quot; -ForegroundColor Cyan
      p $Users = Get-AzureADUser -All $true
      p $Users = $Users | ?{ $_.UserType -eq &apos;Member&apos; -and $_.AccountEnabled -eq $true -and $_.AssignedLicenses -ne $null }
      br
      p Write-Host &quot;Verify you don&apos;t have over 2,500 users&quot; -ForegroundColor Cyan
      p if ($Users.Count -gt 2500) {
      p   throw &quot;You have more than 2500 users. A team in Microsoft Teams cannot have over 2,500 users&quot;
      p }
      br
      p Write-Host &quot;Create Team&quot; -ForegroundColor Cyan
      p $Group = New-Team -DisplayName $TeamName -AccessType Public
      br
      p Write-Host &quot;Adding users to team&quot; -ForegroundColor Cyan
      p foreach ($User in $Users) {
      p   Write-Host &quot;  Adding $($User.UserPrincipalName) to team&quot; -ForegroundColor Cyan
      p   Add-TeamUser -GroupId $Group.GroupId -Role Owner -User $User.UserPrincipalName.ToString()
      p }
      br
      p Write-Host &quot;Disconnect from AzureAD&quot; -ForegroundColor Cyan
      p Disconnect-AzureAD
      br
      p Write-Host &quot;Disconnect from Microsoft Teams&quot; -ForegroundColor Cyan
      p Disconnect-MicrosoftTeams
      br
      p # END OF SCRIPT
